04527nam a22005535i 9780774852173DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748521737 a10.59962/97807748521732doi  a(DE-B1597)662352  a(OCoLC)741451993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQA76.9.C66bB37 2000eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a321.8/0285/461 aBarney, Darin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrometheus Wired :bThe Hope for Democracy in the Age of Network Technology /cDarin Barney. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tcontents -- tacknowledgments -- tprometheus wired -- ton technology -- tnetworks -- tthe political economy of network technology 1: the mode of production -- tthe political economy of network technology 2: work, consumption, and exchange -- ta standing-reserve of bits -- tgovernment, politics, and democracy: network technology as stand-in -- tnotes -- tbibliography -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom all sides, we hear that computer technology, with its undeniable power to disseminate information and connect individuals, holds enormous potential for a reinvigoration of political life. But will the Internet really spark a democratic revolution? And will the changes it brings be so profound that past political thought will be of little use in helping us to understand them? In Prometheus Wired, Darin Barney debunks claims that a networked society will provide the infrastructure for a political revolution and shows that the resources we need for understanding and making sound judgments about this new technology are surprisingly close at hand. By looking to thinkers who grappled with the relationship of society and technology, such as Plato, Aristotle, Marx, and Heidegger, Barney critically examines such assertions about the character of digital networks. Along the way, Barney offers an eye-opening history of digital networks and then explores a wide range of contemporary issues, such as electronic commerce, telecommuting, privacy, virtual community, digital surveillance, and the possibility of sovereign governance in an age of global networks. Ultimately, Barney argues that instead of placing power back in the hands of the public, a networked economy seems to exacerbate the worst features of industrial capitalism, and, in terms of the surveillance and control it exerts, reduces our political freedom. Of vital interest to politicians, communicators, and anyone concerned about the future of democracy in the digital age, Prometheus Wired adds a provocative new voice to the debate swirling around "the Net" and the ways in which it will, or will not, change our political lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy. 0aInformation technology -- Political aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485217340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774852173423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774852173/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles